@article{Lupo2006,
abstract = {The CNS is highly regionalized along both its anteropost-erior (AP) and dorsoventral (DV) axes. AP regionalization of the CNS is clearly evident from the localization of the cerebral cortex and eyes at the anterior end and spinal cord at the posterior end. Similarly, different neurons and neural structures originate at specific DV positions of the neural tube; for example, motor and sensory neurons form in the ventral and dorsal spinal cord, respectively; in the brain, structures such as the hypothalamus and the substantia nigra are ventrally positioned, whereas the cerebral cortex and cerebellum occupy dorsal locations. In addition, subtler aspects of neural cell development, such as the rate of proliferation, the timing of differentiation and the targeting of axonal connections, are all tightly dependent on the position of progenitor cells along the AP and DV axes of the CNS 1. This complex anatomical organization of the mature CNS is anticipated by molecular regionalization of the neuroepithelium at early stages of CNS development. The early neural plate is already subdivided into a complex grid of molecularly distinct progenitor regions, each of which expresses specific transcription factors 2,3. Although the expression of most of these transcription factors is sharply confined along both the AP and DV axes, few of them are restricted to a single progenitor domain. Rather, a unique combination of transcription factors is expressed over time in each progenitor domain 4,5 , and it is these transcriptional codes that specify distinct regions of the CNS. The earliest steps of this process seem to be less complex than downstream events, and recently some unifying principles have emerged. First, the initial stages of neural patterning are controlled by secreted extracellular signalling molecules that spread over variable distances across neural tissue. The activities of these signals are spatiotemporally integrated to determine the specific combinations of transcription factors that are activated in distinct AP and DV compartments of the CNS. Second, there are a limited number of signals involved in this process and the reiterated action of these signals at different AP and DV levels is sufficient to account for most CNS patterning and regionalization 6,7. In this review, we discuss new developments in the study of CNS regionalization, focusing on the signalling systems that control the specification of ventral cell types across the CNS. We concentrate on mechanisms of ventral specification operating in the spinal cord, telen cephalon and eye (FIG. 1). These three structures are located at different AP levels of the CNS, and, excitingly, recent research indicates that the ventral patterning of all of these structures can be largely explained by a few conserved basic molecular mechanisms. First, specification of ventral progenitor domains in the CNS requires nodal and hedgehog (HH) signalling, and inhibition of bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) signalling. Second, HH activity is mostly required to neutralize the repressive form of the GLI3 transcription factor. Third, retinoic acid (RA) is a key signal in the specification of intermediate progenitor domains. Finally, fibroblast growth factor (FGF) signals are also crucial in ventral CNS pattern-ing, especially in the specification of the most ventral progenitor domains. Taken together, these conserved mechanisms provide a simplified picture of ventral neural patterning, which might be applicable to most of Abstract | Dorsoventral patterning of the neural tube has a crucial role in shaping the functional organization of the CNS. It is well established that hedgehog signalling plays a key role in specifying ventral cell types throughout the neuroectoderm, and major progress has been made in elucidating how hedgehog signalling works in this ventral specification. In addition, other molecular pathways, including nodal, retinoic acid and fibroblast growth factor signalling, have been identified as important molecular cues for ventral patterning of the spinal cord, telencephalon and eye. Here, we discuss recent advances in this field, highlighting the emerging interplay of these signalling pathways in the molecular specification of ventral patterning at different rostrocaudal levels of the CNS.},
